## 1. The Mental Model: Hardware Synth

Renoise's interface maps directly to a physical instrument:

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  CASE (Body_Back)                               │
│  ┌───────────────────────────────────────────┐  │
│  │  DISPLAY / SCREEN (Main_Back)             │  │
│  │                                           │  │
│  │  Pattern data, mixer channels, waveforms  │  │
│  │  — the living, scrolling content          │  │
│  │                                           │  │
│  └───────────────────────────────────────────┘  │
│                                                 │
│  [Button] [Button]  ◉ Knob   ═══ Slider        │
│  Transport, toolbars, panels — the controls     │
│                                                 │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

- **`Main_Back`** is the **screen/display** — where data lives. It occupies ~47% of pixels.
- **`Body_Back`** is the **chassis/case** — where controls live. It occupies ~19-23% of pixels.

Together they own **65-70% of every pixel on screen.** Get these two right and the theme is already half-designed.

### The Skeuomorphic Insight

Think of any hardware synth, sampler, or drum machine:

| Hardware Part | Renoise Element | Character |
|---|---|---|
| LCD/LED display | `Main_Back` | Glowing, recessed, data-dense |
| Metal/plastic case | `Body_Back` | Solid, tactile, structural |
| Screen text | `Main_Font` | Sharp, high-contrast against display |
| Panel labels | `Body_Font` | Printed, readable against case |
| Rubber buttons | `Button_Back` | Raised, pressable |
| Knob caps | `Slider` | Distinct, grabbable |
| Status LEDs | `VuMeter_Meter` | Bright, signal |

This metaphor is **not mandatory** but it's why some themes feel "right" — they trigger the same spatial logic musicians already have from using gear.

